description: GSAP animation architecture and patterns
globs: ["**/*.js"]
alwaysApply: true
---

This project uses GSAP and ScrollTrigger for scroll-based storytelling animations.

Architecture principles:

Animations must be separated into logical modules:

- gsap-setup.js
- scroll-scenes.js
- cursor-effects.js
- main.js

Never mix all animations in one file.

GSAP setup must be centralized.

Example setup pattern:

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger)

Use timelines for sequences instead of multiple standalone tweens.

Preferred pattern:

const tl = gsap.timeline({
  scrollTrigger: {
    trigger: ".section",
    start: "top center",
    end: "bottom center",
    scrub: true
  }
})

tl.from(".title", {
  y: 40,
  opacity: 0,
  duration: 1
})

Use pinning for storytelling sections when appropriate.

Example pin pattern:

ScrollTrigger.create({
  trigger: ".hero",
  start: "top top",
  end: "+=200%",
  pin: true,
  scrub: true
})

Performance rules:

- animate only transform and opacity
- avoid animating width/height/top/left
- avoid heavy DOM reads inside scroll callbacks
- batch animations when possible

Use matchMedia for responsive animation logic.

Example:

ScrollTrigger.matchMedia({

  "(min-width: 1024px)": function() {

    // desktop animations

  },

  "(max-width: 1023px)": function() {

    // mobile animations

  }

})

Cursor must generate clean, readable animation code suitable for production.

Avoid overly complex animation unless requested.
Prefer subtle motion suitable for premium storytelling websites.